{"about 1434–":"about 1434–Deceased","1438–Female":"1438–Deceased","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1462–Male":"1462–Deceased","1464–Male":"1464–Deceased","1466–Male":"1466–Deceased","1468–Female":"1468–Deceased","1470–Female":"1470–Deceased","1472–Female":"1472–Deceased","1474–Female":"1474–Deceased","1434–Male":"1434–Deceased","abt. 1466":"about 1466","abt. 1468":"about 1468","abt. 1474":"about 1474","1462":"1462","1472":"1472","1460":"1460","abt. 1464":"about 1464","1470":"1470","abt 1462":"about 1462","abt. 1470":"about 1470","abt. 1472":"about 1472","abt. 1460":"about 1460","1468":"1468","1434":"1434","1466":"1466","1464":"1464","1474":"1474","about 1434":"about 1434","1438":"1438","of Altgwawddu, Glam., Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","of Altgwawrddu, Glam., Wales.":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Geza, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Lewis","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Lewis</i>, <i>Leweis</i>, <i>Lowis</i>, from ancient Germanic (originally West Frankish) <i>Hludwig</i> (itself from <i>hlōd-</i> ‘fame, famous’ + <i>wīg-</i> ‘battle’). This was Latinized as <i>Ludovicus</i> and <i>Chlodovisus</i>, which were gallicized as <i>Clovis</i> or <i>Clouis</i>, French <i>Louis</i>. The name may also appear as <i>Lawis</i>, <i>Laweys</i>, <i>Lawes</i>, by unrounding of the vowel of <i>Lowis</i> on the analogy of the variation between <i>Low</i> and <i>Law</i> as pet forms of Middle English <i>Lourence</i> alias <i>Laurence</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Laws   2 and compare   Lawrence  .","Welsh: adopted for the Welsh personal name <i>Llywelyn</i> (see   Llewellyn  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’. This is one of the most common Old Irish personal names. It is derived from <i>Lugh</i> ‘brightness’, which was the name of a Celtic god."],"variants":[{"name":"Laws","meanings":["English: variant of   Law   (pet form of   Lawrence  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish or Irish   McLeish  . Compare   McLaws  ."]},{"name":"Lewison","meanings":["Welsh and English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Lewis   (in Wales this was taken as equivalent to the Welsh personal name   Llewelyn  ). In North America, this surname has reportedly absorbed in some cases the Greek patronymic   Iliopoulos  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name <i>Lewi</i>, Polish-influenced form of   Levy  ."]},{"name":"McGlew","meanings":["Irish: most probably from <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’, a Gaelic personal name (referencing the god Lugh), sometimes Anglicized as   Lewis  . However, both Woulfe and MacLysaght consider <i>McGlew</i> to be a shortened form of <b>Mac Dhuinnshléibhe</b> (see   McAleavey   and   Dunleavy  )."]},{"name":"Lowis","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewis   1."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Ap Lewis was born about 1434, in Glamorgan, Wales. He had at least 4 sons and 4 daughters with Margaret Coch Ap Lewis."},"et":{"about 1434–":"umbes 1434–Surnud","1438–Female":"1438–Surnud","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1462–Male":